Nooshi is one of my favorite sushi spots in DC because of the fun rooftop and great happy hour specials. “Crazy hour” even extends to weekends (4:30 to 7 p.m.) — and all cold Saki and cocktails are 1/2 off. While you’ve got some specialty rolls that can run anywhere from about $8 to $12, you’ve got a whole variety of normal rolls that start at about $5 for 6 prices. It’s a great date spot for something more casual and fun, but still high quality sushi. Or a fun place to go with a group because of the amazing deal on drinks for “crazy hour.” I’ve had about all of their noodle and rice dishes as well — good quality and a great quantity (aka leftovers for a second meal to take home). Service is always super efficient too. Definitely a spot to hit up on the regular for a sushi fan in SE DC.

This was my second visit. The first was about a year ago and food was average. This time I was very disappointed with one of the dishes we ordered- the char siu with ramen. The liquid in the dish tasted awful - had a very cloudy appearance and tasted like soapy water. In addition there were only two pieces of the roast pork in the entire rather large bowl and they had almost no taste. We did like the spring rolls and the “Godzilla sushi. Maybe the sushi is what to order here. While the service was good and wait staff pleasant, the atmosphere was rather dreary. I probably won’t go back.

There is fun use of glass and text to tease the hungry consumer as they can see there food being prepared behind a glass plane frosted walls to the kitchen; with the phase "Peeking Duck" left as clear gloss, allowing the clientele to take a "Peek" at the wizardry required to make Peeking Duck.

I took the Metro to the Eastern Market Station to find a few city geocaches. One of them was just outside Nooshi, so it's where I decided to have dinner. I didn't know what to expect at first because access to the restaurant is via a sketchy narrow walkway between the building and a parking lot, but the interior looked comfortable. The decor and lighting were simple but tasteful. Also, there were plenty of two-seater booths, which are great for single diners like myself.  The menu is an Asian fusion mix, with sushi, Thai, and Malaysian items. Since I like Malaysian, I ordered the mee goreng and chicken satay. I wouldn't say either of those were 100% authentic but those were pretty good for a restaurant that does not specialize in Malaysian food. I liked the presentation and overall flavor but wished they had actual peanut sauce for the satay.  Service was rather good, with frequent checks to see if I needed anything. They were quick with the water glass refill as well.

Would not honor their coupon!  I tried to order online using a 15% off coupon code sent from ChowNow for Nooshi.  Neither the Chownow nor Nooshi site would accept the coupon code, and after about 45 minutes on the phone with both companies, we found out the the coupon they emailed was a mistake and they would not honor it.  To clarify, they emailed this to us; we didn't find this on some discount website on the darkweb.  They just decided it was a mistake and it that expired the day it was sent, not the 29 days stated in the email.  Neither company seemed too upset that they emailed this code out and weren't honoring it.  They offered us 10% off for our trouble.  But since we were told we would get 15%, and we spend 45 minutes on the phone, I don't feel this was enough.

After meaning to try Nooshi for over a year now, I finally made the plunge, despite the mediocre Yelp reviews.  Nooshi is kind of in a back alley off Barracks Row, adjacent to Tash, with a really cool street art on the side of the building as you walk toward the entrance. The décor was surprisingly hip, and well done, masking the fact that you're in a back alley. The rooftop deck was also very nice with an adjacent bar that would be really fun for Happy Hour.  With tons of Sushi and Thai options, I settled on a Sashimi platter, which was fresh and excellent and the presentation was more upscale than expected.  Overall, I really enjoyed my dinner and will definitely be back  Disclaimer: I have been on the Paleo diet for the past few years, so my restaurant/supermarket reviews come from that perspective (ie no pizza reviews for this guy)

The decor and atmosphere of this restaurant is really cool and I've never had to wait for a table. The sushi is good--nothing too exciting and definitely not the best I've ever had, but good. Definitely a good addition to Barrack's Row.
